text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Sign Language Acquisition%0a%0a:Author: leah_w%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAcquisition of sign language and the similarity to spoken language%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aSign language is a language of its own and children learn to sign around the same age as children who learn spoken language. In addition, children learn sign language just like they learn spoken language, as they pick it up from it being used around them. The major difference is that the infants need to know where to look in order to learn the language, rather than just hearing the language. An interesting thing about babies learning sign language is that infant-directed sign language attracts their attention more due to the slow speed of the sign and the large movements. While infants learn sign language, they tend to have a lot of repetition and the location of their signs are off. Just liken spoken language acquisition, infants go through a babble with their hands before they learn words, called a manual babble. First words typically will not appear until 10 months of age. The type of words they learn first is similar to the words that spoken language children learn first, words about their experiences. At 12 months of age, a child can combine a gesture with a word (called semantic one-sign stage) and by 16 months they are at semantic two-sign stage. The difference between these two stages is that the first one deals with a point and word of the same meaning and the second one the point and the word have different meanings. From here, children can learn morphology which uses non-manual markers and space. The non-manual markers can include facial expressions. Non-manual markers are hard for children to master, as they are not fully able to master them until 12 years of age, even though they start learning them at 2 years of age. From here on children learn sentences and structure of a language, at a similar pace to those who learn spoken language. %0a%0aReference: %0aMayberry, R. I., & Squires, B. (2006). Sign language acquisition. Encyclopedia of language and linguistics, 11, 739-43.%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-020019-105180#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Parallels in acquisition of sign and spoken languages %0a-> - MitulS%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAnother interesting parallel between the acquisition of signed and spoken languages is the gradual change in the language application aspects that children pay attention to. For sign language, infants start out paying attention to larger, more grandiose movements rather than smaller, more dexterous ones because those are more recognizable and repeatable to them at that stage. Similarly, infants acquire simpler bilabial sounds before ones that are more hidden in the mouth or those that incorporate teeth.%0aAs they grow, they become aware of the more minute and difficult to produce language aspects, such as finger movements or alveolar location sounds.%0a%0aThat there is a lack of usage of sign language in most communities poses a problem for children acquiring signed languages. Similar to spoken language acquisition requiring visual cues for the child to pick up on, signed languages require visual cues that are ideally provided for the child on a regular basis. While regular usage of general signed language helps alleviate the issue, there can still be disconnects. Hearing parents may struggle to understand what kinds of cues infants can easily pick up on and fail to properly utilize signed "baby talk" that deaf parents have shown to be skilled at.%0a%0aSource:%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_acquisition_by_deaf_children%0ahttps://www.dana.org/article/children-need-natural-languages-signed-or-spoken/%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210505-020019-105180#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210508-132035-632750#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-08.05.2021 - 06:20-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210508-132035-632750 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Abi_S%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Language development '''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aIt's pretty interesting how sign language development and spoken language are learned at a similar pace. I wonder at the brain level, what's occurring (what differs in processes) %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-132035-632750#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
