diff:1620180019:1620070043:=49,65c49%0a%3c #foxbegin 210505-020019-105180#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Parallels in acquisition of sign and spoken languages %0a%3c -> - MitulS%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Another interesting parallel between the acquisition of signed and spoken languages is the gradual change in the language application aspects that children pay attention to. For sign language, infants start out paying attention to larger, more grandiose movements rather than smaller, more dexterous ones because those are more recognizable and repeatable to them at that stage. Similarly, infants acquire simpler bilabial sounds before ones that are more hidden in the mouth or those that incorporate teeth.%0a%3c As they grow, they become aware of the more minute and difficult to produce language aspects, such as finger movements or alveolar location sounds.%0a%3c %0a%3c That there is a lack of usage of sign language in most communities poses a problem for children acquiring signed languages. Similar to spoken language acquisition requiring visual cues for the child to pick up on, signed languages require visual cues that are ideally provided for the child on a regular basis. While regular usage of general signed language helps alleviate the issue, there can still be disconnects. Hearing parents may struggle to understand what kinds of cues infants can easily pick up on and fail to properly utilize signed "baby talk" that deaf parents have shown to be skilled at.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source:%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_acquisition_by_deaf_children%0a%3c https://www.dana.org/article/children-need-natural-languages-signed-or-spoken/%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210505-020019-105180#%0a---%0a> %0a
